  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">The stages of an appeal </h2>

  <h3>1. Submit appeal </h3>
  <p>Start your appeal using the online service. You’ll need to have your original planning application details to hand.</p>
  <p>After submission you will need to send a copy of your appeal to the local planning department.</p>

  <h3>2. The local planning department submit their case file</h3>
  <p>The local planning department will submit documents and details they used to make a decision on your application to us.</p>

  <h3>3. Site visit</h3>
  <p>An Inspector may need to visit the appeal site. We’ll contact you to confirm a date and time.</p>

  <h3>4. Decision</h3>
  <p>The Inspector will consider the evidence from all parties to make a decision. </p>
  <p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/appeals-average-timescales-for-arranging-inquiries-and-hearings" target="_blank">Check how long householder planning appeal decisions may take</a>.</p>

  <h3>How your appeal will be decided​ ​</h3>
  <p>Householder planning appeals are always decided by written representations, which means the Inspector looks at written evidence from all parties to reach a decision.</p>
